    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Where's the Outrage?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Elliot Bergstein letter responds to July 17 article on resurgence of violent crime in Los Angeles</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Various factors contribute to a resurgence of violent crime in Los Angeles (news article, July 17). Drugs, guns, an ineffective correctional system and a lack of suitable summer jobs can all be blamed, but until we fully sense the injustice of one citizen assaulting another, we will not mobilize to deal appropriately with any of these and related issues.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Various factors contribute to a resurgence of violent crime in Los Angeles (news article, July 17). Drugs, guns, an ineffective correctional system and a lack of suitable summer jobs can all be blamed, but until we fully sense the injustice of one citizen assaulting another, we will not mobilize to deal appropriately with any of these and related issues.</p>
        <p>The video in which police were filmed beating Rodney King, and the public outrage that followed, brought change in police procedures. Civilians assaulted by other civilians must elicit the same sympathy.</p>
        <p>DAVID ELLIOT BERGSTEIN  Brooklyn, July 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
